Introduction¶

The Goal of this exercise is to understand the Telco Data From here. </br> How are various factors correlated to each other and the churn value.</br> Analyse what are the factors that are diriving the Churn. </br> Can we predict a customer churn</br>

In [10]:
def add_date(idx):
    val = math.floor(idx/541)
    
    u = datetime.datetime.strptime("2021-06-05","%Y-%m-%d")    
    d = datetime.timedelta(days=7*val)
    return u + d

Now that we have numerical catagorical fatures. we can test the corelation between them as well using Cramer'sV

In [42]:
cat_var_conv = ['genderN', 'PartnerN', 'DependentsN', 'PhoneServiceN', 'MultipleLinesN', 'InternetServiceN', 'OnlineSecurityN', 'DeviceProtectionN', 'TechSupportN', 'StreamingTVN', 'StreamingMoviesN', 'ContractN', 'PaperlessBillingN', 'PaymentMethodN', 'ChurnN']
In [43]:
def cramers_v(x, y):
    confusion_matrix = pd.crosstab(x,y)
    chi2 = ss.chi2_contingency(confusion_matrix)[0]
    n = confusion_matrix.sum().sum()
    phi2 = chi2/n
    r,k = confusion_matrix.shape
    phi2corr = max(0, phi2-((k-1)*(r-1))/(n-1))
    rcorr = r-((r-1)**2)/(n-1)
    kcorr = k-((k-1)**2)/(n-1)
    return np.sqrt(phi2corr/min((kcorr-1),(rcorr-1)))
In [44]:
df_raw_data_corr = df_raw_data[cat_var_conv].corr(method = cramers_v)

RandomForestClassifier

In [53]:
rd_metrics = {}
rd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(criterion = 'entropy', max_depth = 11, max_features = 'auto', 
                                min_samples_leaf = 2, min_samples_split = 3, n_estimators = 130)
rd_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
# accuracy score, confusion matrix and classification report of random forest
rd_clf_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, rd_clf.predict(X_test))
print(f"Training Accuracy of Random Forest Classifier is {accuracy_score(y_train, rd_clf.predict(X_train))}")
print(f"Test Accuracy of Random Forest Classifier is {rd_clf_acc} \n")
class_report_rd = classification_report(y_test, rd_clf.predict(X_test), output_dict =True)
print(f"Confusion Matrix :- \n{confusion_matrix(y_test, rd_clf.predict(X_test))}\n")
print(f"Classification Report :- \n {classification_report(y_test, rd_clf.predict(X_test))}")
rd_metrics['accuracy'] = class_report_rd['accuracy']
rd_metrics['precision'] = class_report_rd['weighted avg']['precision']
rd_metrics['recall'] = class_report_rd['weighted avg']['recall']
rd_metrics['f1-score'] = class_report_rd['weighted avg']['f1-score']
model_output['Random_Forest_Classifier'] = rd_metrics

Model Exploration¶

We can explore following models for this predictive activity -

Naive Bayes

  • Good to explore one of classic models, Many times the classics work the best, esp on small dataset we have like right now

kNN (K Nearest Neighbour)

  • kNN seem to work for Churn prediction usually

Decision Tree Classifier

  • Since we have a lot of features. Tree based algorithms generally work quite good with lots of featurers

Random Forest Classifier

  • Since we have a lot of features and we can play aroung with the depth of trees, it is worth exploring the random forest classifier as well. One caution for Random forest is that since we have less data. this model would be prone to overfitting
